*The '''Boarding School''' was opened in 1890, and is located on the top floor of the Main School. It provides a modern boarding environment for 65 students, with Years 6 to 9 housed in Mance corridor in rooms containing 3 to 6 girls, 10 and 11 in Taylor corridor in twin rooms, and Year&nbsp;12 in McKenzie corridor with private rooms.    
*The '''Boat Shed''' is a [[lease]]d facility for [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]], located at the Drummoyne Rowing Club in the nearby suburb of [[Drummoyne, New South Wales|Drummoyne]]. PLC began its rowing programme here in 1994.     
*'''College Hall''' is the original [[Assembly Hall|school hall]]. Opened in 1890, it is now used for [[chapel]] services, social events and school meetings.   
*'''The Croydon''' is a [[Creative Arts]] Centre featuring [[Drawing]], [[Paint]], [[Ceramic]], [[Food Technology]], [[Woodworking]], [[Textiles]], [[Photography]] and [[Printmaking|Print]] studios, together with computing facilities and The Adelaide Perry Gallery, an [[art gallery]] with regular exhibitions open to the school and community. Formerly the Croydon [[Public house|Hotel]], the facility was purchased in 1997 and opened after conversions in 2000.<ref name="SMHPatty">{{cite news | first = Anna| last = Patty| title = All down the pub for a bit of culture, girls| url = http://newsstore.smh.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=smh&kw=%22All+down+the+pub+for+a+bit+of+culture+girls%22&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=entire&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=news970510_0010_4318| work = News| publisher = ''The Sun Herald''| page = 86| date = 1997-05-10| accessdate = 2007-10-10}}</ref>  
*'''Drummond Field''' is a large [[Playing field|sporting field]] suitable for activities like hockey, athletics (track and field) and soccer.<ref name="PLCFacilities">{{cite web|url = http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/facilities.asp|title = Facilities|accessdate = 2007-11-05|work = PLC Sydney|publisher = Presbyterian Ladies' College}}</ref> It was opened in 1989 after the purchase of property and land between the school and the railway line,<ref name="GH137">{{cite book| last = McFarlane| first = John| title = The Golden Hope: Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney 1888-1988| year = 1988| pages = p. 137| chapter =Preparation For Expansion 1977-1985}}</ref> and sections of Grosvenor, Meta and Elizabeth Streets.<ref name="FacilitiesHistory"/>  
*'''Evandale''' is the [[Preparatory school|prep-school]] housing girls from Reception to [[Year Two (School)|Year 2]]. Purchased in 1992 and opened 1993, it is situated across the road from the main campus and was formerly The Evandale School, a private school for primary aged students with disabilities.<ref name="FacilitiesHistory"/>     
*The '''Freda Whitlam School of Science''' is a three storey building housing science facilities,<ref name="PLCFacilities"/> opened in 1997 by notable former Principal, Freda Whitlam.
