== Curriculum ==
The Presbyterian Ladies' College is a [[comprehensive school]] with a traditional academic approach designed to prepare students for attending a [[university]].<ref name=Curriculum>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/curriculum.asp |title=Curriculum Overview |accessdate=2007-06-30 |work=Curriculum|publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College }}</ref> The school is registered and accredited with the [[Board of Studies|New South Wales Board of Studies]],<ref name=BoardofStudies>{{cite web |url=http://www.boardofstudies.nsw.edu.au/ebos/static/AccredSchoolsP.htm |title=Non-Government Registered Schools List|accessdate=2007-10-29 |date =2007-10-18 |work= Letter P - Board of Studies NSW |publisher=New South Wales Government}}</ref> and therefore follows the mandated [[curriculum]] for all years.

===Primary===
[[Image:PLCFete1948.jpg|thumb|190px|PLC primary students at the 1948 school fête]]
Students in stages 1 to 3 ([[Kindergarten]] to [[Year Six (School)|Year 6]]) study the six Key Learning Areas: English, Mathematics, Human Society and its Environment (HSIE), Science and Technology, [[Creative Arts]], Personal Development, Health and Physical Education (PD/H/PE). The youngest students also follow the [[Reggio Emilia approach]] to education.  Specialist extension courses are offered to select students from [[Year Two (School)|Year 2]] to 6 with gifts and talents in special areas (SPEC).<ref name="Curriculum"/>

===Secondary===
Subjects offered to stage 4 students ([[Year Seven (School)|Years 7]] and 8) include: English, Mathematics, Science, [[Geography]], [[History]], [[French language|French]], [[Standard Mandarin|Mandarin]], [[Latin]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[German language|German]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Design and Technology]], [[Visual Arts]], [[Music]], PDHPE, [[Computing]] and [[Religious Education]]. The "Excelsior class" is an [[Gifted education|enrichment programme]] offered to gifted students in this stage and includes additional classes such as [[Philosophy]] and [[Olympiad]] activities.<ref name="Curriculum"/>
[[Image:PLCSyd1930.jpg|thumb|left|240px|PLC pupils doing eurythmics, ''c.'' 1930s]]
In stage 5 ([[Year Nine (School)|Years 9]] and 10), students are prepared for the [[School Certificate]] and study a programme that comprises two elective classes and Religious Education, as well as the courses mandated by the Board of Studies. The compulsory core subjects are: English, Mathematics, Science, Australian History and Geography, and PDHPE. Electives are chosen from: Elective History, Elective Geography, French, German, Mandarin, Latin, Japanese, Italian, Commerce, Drama, Design and Technology, Textiles and Design, Music, Visual Arts, and Physical Activity and Sports Science. 
In [[Year Ten (School)|Year 10]], the Excelsior class begins its study of the 1&ndash;Unit [[Higher School Certificate]] (HSC) course in Studies of Religion.<ref name="Curriculum"/>

In the final school stage ([[Year Eleven (School)|Years 11]] and 12) students are prepared for the New South Wales HSC. The curriculum at this stage has a clear university orientation. The Board of Studies requires stage 6 students to study a minimum of 12&nbsp;units in the Preliminary Year and 10&nbsp;units in their HSC Year (most subjects being worth 2&nbsp;units). [[New South Wales HSC English|HSC English]] is compulsory; Standard and Advanced Extension courses, as well as 2-unit English as a Second Language are also offered. Students may then choose from all levels of Mathematics, Senior Science, Biology, Chemistry, Physics, Modern History, Ancient History, Business Studies, Economics, Geography, Legal studies, French, German, Latin, Japanese, Italian, Indonesian (Beginners), Mandarin, Design and Technology, Textiles and Design, [[Food Technology]], Visual Arts, Music (Course 1 and 2), Drama and PDHPE.<ref name="Curriculum"/>

University entry levels are high following the completion of stage&nbsp;6. Each year approximately 50% of graduating PLC students receive a [[Universities Admission Index]] (UAI) higher than 90.<ref name=Prospectus>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/media/070524_prospectus.pdf |title=Prospectus |accessdate=2007-06-30 |format =PDF |work=Enrolment Enquiry|publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College }}</ref> In the 2006 Higher School Certificate, a PLC student received a perfect UAI score of 100,<ref name=IWCNJ>{{cite news| first = Leesa| last = Smith| title = Nikki notches a perfect result| url = http://www.villagevoice.com.au/article/20070117/NWS05/701170352&SearchID=73295770208658/Nikki+notches+a+perfect+result| work = Education| publisher = ''Inner Western Courier''| date = 2007-01-18| accessdate = 2007-10-08}}</ref> and in 2007 ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Australia)|The Daily Telegraph]]'' named PLC the best-performing independent school in Sydney's inner&ndash;west.<ref name=HSC07>{{cite news| title = How schools performed by region| url = http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,22975570-5006009,00.html| work = NSW/ACT| publisher = ''The Daily Telegraph''| location = Sydney| date = 2007-12-27| accessdate = 2008-02-06 }}</ref>

===Special education===
PLC also offers a unique [[special education]] unit catering to students with mild to moderate [[intellectual disabilities]]. The transition programme was developed in 1992 in response to a decision by academic staff to provide a special-needs stream. Through this unit, up to 20 girls between the ages of 11 and 18 are provided with an individual curriculum incorporating mainstream classes where possible.<ref name=Specialneeds>{{cite news| first = Perrie| last = Croshaw| title = Special needs met| url = http://newsstore.smh.com.au/apps/viewDocument.ac?page=1&sy=smh&kw=%22PLC+Sydney%22&pb=all_ffx&dt=selectRange&dr=10years&so=relevance&sf=text&sf=headline&rc=10&rm=200&sp=nrm&clsPage=1&docID=SMH0702086P6N71NB3U7| work = Supplement| publisher = ''The Sydney Morning Herald''| page = 2| date = 2007-02-08| accessdate = 2007-10-08}}</ref>

Senior students focus on the Board of Studies Life Skills programme. Girls spend time as residential students in the on-campus Transition House, learning to manage their lives independently. Transition students also run an outdoor café to gain small business skills.<ref name=Specialneeds/>

== Co-curriculum ==   
=== Sport ===   
[[Image:PLCswimming.jpg|thumb|220px|PLC swimming carnival, 1948]]
PLC Sydney is arguably one of Australia's best girls' sporting schools.<ref name=Principalswelcome>{{cite web|url = http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public/principalswelcome.PDF|title = Principal's Welcome|accessdate = 2007-10-08|last = McKeith|first = William|format = PDF|work = The Principal|publisher = Presbyterian Ladies' College}}</ref>
The College has been a member of the [[Independent Girls' Schools Sporting Association]] (IGSSA) since its foundation in 1922,<ref name=PLCSportintro>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/index.html |title= Overview of Sports at PLC|accessdate=2007-10-08 |work= PLC Sydney Sport & PDHPE |publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College}}</ref> and through this association senior students compete against 27 other girls' schools in graded weekend sports and carnivals. Sports available to students through IGSSA include [[swimming]], [[diving]], [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]], [[Cross country running|cross country]], [[Athletics (track and field)|athletics]], [[gymnastics]], [[softball]], [[tennis]], [[basketball]], [[soccer]], [[Field hockey|field hockey]], [[netball]], [[cricket]] and [[water polo]].<ref name=IGSSAintro>{{cite web |url=http://igssa.ahigs.nsw.edu.au/DeskTopDefault.aspx?tabid=1 |title=Welcome to IGSSA |accessdate=2007-10-08 |work=IGSSA Online |publisher=Independent Girls' Schools Sporting Association}}</ref> The College also offers sports such as [[skiing]], [[snowboarding]], [[Equestrianism|equestrian]] and [[badminton]] through other competitions.<ref name=PLCSportintro/> In 2007 PLC won three IGSSA carnival premierships: in diving (for the ninth consecutive year), swimming,<ref name=IWCSwimming>{{cite news| first = Chloe| last = Adamson| title = PLC breaks 10-year drought| url = http://digitaledition.innerwestcourier.com.au/| work = Sport| publisher = ''The Inner Western Courier''| page = 191| date = 2007-10-08| accessdate = 2007-10-08}}</ref> and gymnastics.<ref name=IGSSAGym07>{{cite web |url=http://igssa.ahigs.nsw.edu.au/uploads/GYM2007WAG(working).xls |title= WAG and Overall Results 2007 |accessdate=2007-10-29 |last= Gowan|first=A |date=2007-10-29 |format=xls|work= Carnivals - Gymnastics|publisher=Independent Girls' Schools Sporting Association}}</ref>
  
Primary school girls have the opportunity to participate in interschool sports through PLC's membership in the New South Wales branch of the [[Junior School Heads Association of Australia]] (JSHAA).<ref name=PLCSportintro/>  Students with special sporting talent are provided a pathway to compete at the highest level available at PLC, IGSSA/JSHAA, Combined Independent Schools, state representation at School Sport Australia, and [[Commonwealth games|Commonwealth]] and [[Olympic games|Olympic]] level.<ref name=Sport>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/specialities_sport.asp |title=Specialities - Sport |accessdate=2007-04-23 |work=Cocurricular|publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College}}</ref> 

In September 2007, the college broke the under-19 female Australian record for 24-hour non-stop rowing, with a distance of {{convert|337|km|mi|0}}.<ref name=RowingRecord>{{cite news| first = Leesa| last = Smith| title = An oarsome fundraising effort| url = http://digitaledition.innerwestcourier.com.au/| work = Learn| publisher = ''The Inner Western Courier''| page = 43| date = 2007-09-11| accessdate = 2007-10-08}}</ref> Also in 2007, PLC was named the New South Wales School Snowsports Club of the Year by the NSW Snowsports Association,<ref name=Cluboftheyear>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public/newsletter/pubnewsletter.pdf |title= PLC Sydney wins school snowsports club of the year! |accessdate=2007-11-11 |date=2007-11-08 |format=PDF|work= PLC Connections|publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College|pages = p. 7}}</ref> later winning the national award at the 2007 Ski and Snowboard Australia Awards.<ref name=AustCluboftheyear>{{cite web |url=http://www.interschools.org.au/sitePage.asp?siteid=3&pageid=39 |title= 2007 Ski and Snowboard Australia Award Winners |accessdate=2007-12-24 |date=2007-11-27 |work=NSW Interschools |publisher=Snow Sports Development Foundation}}</ref> 

The 2008 rowing season has been one of the school's best to date. In March, the PLC 1st Eight crew won the Schoolgirl Eight race at the [[Independent Girls' Schools Sporting Association#Rowing|IGSSA regatta]] for the first time in the school's history.<ref name=IGSSARegatta08>{{cite web|url= http://www.rowingnsw.asn.au/regattas/07-08/igssa/2008_AHIGS-IGSSA_results.html#R21|title= AHIGS-IGSSA - Sunday, 2 March 2008 |accessdate= 2008-03-11 |date= 2008-03-02 |work= AHIGS-IGSSA Regatta|publisher= NSW Rowing Association Inc}}</ref> This crew was also successful at the 2008 [[Rowing Australia|Australian Rowing]] Championships, winning the A Final of the Schoolgirls Eight race (the Sydney Cup), ahead of [[St Catherine's School, Toorak]] and Pymble Ladies' College, thus ranking them as the best schoolgirl eight in Australia.<ref name=AustNationalsresults>{{cite web|url= http://www.rowingnsw.asn.au/regattas/07-08/nationals/Day7_results.pdf|title= 2008 Australian Rowing Championships - Day 7|accessdate= 2008-03-11 |date= 2008-03-09 |format= PDF |work= 2008 Australian Rowing Championships and Interstate Regatta|publisher= NSW Rowing Association Inc|pages= p.17}}</ref><ref name=Great8>{{cite news| first = Fiona| last = Brady| title = PLC's 'great eight' take national championship| url = http://www.innerwestweekly.com.au/article/2008/03/26/2177_sports.html| work = Sport| publisher = ''Inner-West Weekly''| location = Sydney, NSW | date = 2008-03-26| accessdate = 2008-03-26}}</ref>

=== Ensembles ===   
Junior and Senior School students can participate in [[musical ensemble]]s, both selective and non-selective, including several bands, string orchestras, a full school orchestra, [[chamber music]] ensembles, [[Choir|choral]] groups and several smaller instrumental and vocal groups.<ref name=Ensembles>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/extra_curricular_ensembles.asp |title=Extra Curricular - Ensembles |accessdate=2007-04-23 |work=Cocurricular|publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College}}</ref>

PLC also features the only all-girl [[Pipe band|Pipes and Drums corps]] in the state of New South Wales. The Pipes and Drums corps plays an important role in official school functions and traditions, and members also have the opportunity to perform at community events, combine with other schools for performances, and attend [[eisteddfod]]s, competitions, camps and musical tours.<ref name="Ensembles"/>

=== Debating and public speaking ===      
One of the strengths of PLC Sydney is their long history of achievement in [[debate|debating]] and [[public speaking]]. The college has competed in the Independent Schools Debating Association (ISDA) for the past five years<ref name=ISDA>{{cite web |url=http://isdadebating.info/schools/schoolsfr.html |title=Participating Schools |accessdate=2007-06-21 |work=Schools |publisher=Independent Schools Debating Association}}</ref> and has had a long-standing commitment to the [[Association of Heads of Independent Girls' Schools#Archdale Debating Competition|Archdale Debating Competition]]. PLC students have had success at the semi-final level,<ref name=Debating>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/specialities_debating.asp |title=Specialities - Debating |accessdate=2007-04-23 |work=Cocurricular |publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College}}</ref> and they won the competition in 2006.<ref name=Archdale>{{cite web |url=http://archdale.info/results/resultsfr.html |title= Archdale Shield |accessdate=2007-04-23 |year =2006 |work=Competition Results|publisher=Archdale Debating Competition}}</ref>

PLC Sydney enters teams in the Junior and Senior sections of the [[Association of Heads of Independent Girls' Schools]] (AHIGS) [[Association of Heads of Independent Girls' Schools#Festival of Speech|Festival of Speech]], producing the best results of any AHIGS school over the history of the competition, with 10 consecutive wins in the competition's 12-year history. 

Students may also participate in the Macquarie Cup and the [[Commonwealth Bank]] Senior Debating, vying with students from a range of [[Public school|public]], [[Catholic school|Catholic]] and independent schools. There are also Social Debates with surrounding schools as well as a regular competition with [[Trinity Grammar School (New South Wales)|Trinity Grammar School]] called the PLC/Trinity Challenge.<ref name="Debating"/>

=== Aid projects ===
The PLC Overseas Aid Fund has been established to enhance the college's work with [[Aid|aid projects]] in [[Developing country|developing countries]], and is an important part of the school's [[Round Square]] membership.<ref name=OverseasAid>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/aid.asp |title=PLC Overseas Aid Fund |accessdate=2007-04-23 |work=Service Learning |publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College }}</ref> Current projects undertaken by the school include the establishment and on-going management of two Kindergartens in [[East Timor]],<ref name=EastTimor>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/east_timor.asp |title=East Timor Project |accessdate=2007-04-23 |work=Service Learning|publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College }}</ref> the management and support of Birla Children's [[Orphanage]] in [[Vietnam]], and the establishment of the "Adopt a School" programme. This programme was developed and is directed by the Principal, Dr McKeith, and matches schools in Australia with schools in [[Sri Lanka]] requiring rebuilding following the 2004 [[Tsunami]]. PLC's school, allocated through this programme, is the Senehasa Counselling, Training and Rehabilitation Centre for Girls.<ref name=AdoptaSchool>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/adopt_a_school.asp |title=Adopt a School |accessdate=2007-04-23 |work=International |publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College}}</ref>

== Fees ==
As with most Australian private schools, PLC receives government funding and therefore only international students pay full fees. For non-international students, 2008 fees range from [[Australian dollar|AU$]]11,360 to $20,150 per year, and more than $32,000 per year for boarding students.<ref name=Fees08/>

PLC Sydney offers [[scholarship]]s and bursaries that provide full or part remission of tuition fees to students who are Australian citizens, Permanent Residents of Australia or refugees. Academic scholarships are based on the results of the [[Australian Council for Educational Research|ACER]] Scholarship Examination, and are typically offered from Year&nbsp;7 onwards. In addition to those awarded for academic performance, PLC also offers music and boarding scholarships. Indigenous Bursaries are available for students of [[Indigenous Australians|Aboriginal]] or [[Torres Strait Islanders|Torres Strait Islander]] background, and are awarded following an interview with the Principal where the situation of the student and family is considered.<ref name=Scholarships>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/scholarships.asp |title=Scholarships and Bursaries |accessdate=2007-12-26 |work=Enrolment |publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College}}</ref>

== Motto and crest ==
[[Image:PLCCigaretteCard.jpg|thumb|150px|Collectable Cigarette card featuring the PLC colours and crest, ''c.'' 1910s]]   
The school [[Coat of arms|crest]] was adopted at a College Council meeting on [[23 August]] [[1888]]. The College Council decided to use the same crest as that used by the [[Presbyterian Church of New South Wales]], with minor modifications.<ref name="GH298"/>

The Church's crest consisted of a shield with the words ''Nec Tamen Consumebatur'' (translated from [[Latin]] as "And yet it was not consumed") surrounding it.<ref name=PresbyterianChurch>{{Citation| year=2004 | title=An Introduction to the Presbyterian Church of Australia | place= Sydney | publisher=Code Committee of the General Assembly of the Presbyterian Church of Australia | volume=1 | pages=p. 21 | url=http://www.presbyterian.org.au/PDF/AnIntroductiont%20thePCABooklet.pdf | format=PDF| accessdate=2007-08-06}}</ref> On the shield were the stars of the [[Southern Cross]], a [[burning bush]], and a [[Latin cross]] in outline. At the base were the [[floral emblem]]s of Scotland, England and Ireland. Surrounding the shield was a border with the words "Presbyterian Church of New South Wales", with a [[Star of David]] placed on top. Behind both shield and borders was the [[Saint Andrew's Cross|cross of St. Andrew]] in blue.<ref name="GH298"/> 
     
The School modified this crest by changing the words "Presbyterian Church of New South Wales" to "Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney", placing a [[Maltese cross]] at the top of the shield and inserting the School [[motto]] ''Sancte Sapienter''. The motto had been adopted by the school on 23 August 1888, and although no [[translation]] was given of the Latin, it may be loosely translated to "be holy wisely" or "holy, wisely."<ref name="GH298"/>

== School badge ==   
The school's highly symbolic badge was inspired by the first Principal, Dr. Marden, and designed in 1888 by the first art teacher, J.A. Bennett. The maiden on the lion represents Knowledge, which is crowned by a tower representing the home, and holding a [[trident]] representing [[Sovereignty]]. A [[laurel wreath]] represents the victory of true womanhood, while the sun symbolises light and energy, and the [[crescent moon]] stands for [[youth]]. The words "Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney" surround the badge.<ref name="GH299"/> 
[[Image:PLCBadge.jpg|left|thumb|160px|PLC Sydney school badge]]
The motto ''All'Ultimo Lavoro'' is [[French (language)|French]] and comes from [[Dante]]. It has variously been translated as: "for the crowning task", "strive for the highest", "the utmost for the highest", or "I work for the highest."<ref name="GH299"/>   
       
The badge is reproduced in the [[leadlight]] over the front door of Shubra Hall,<ref name="GH299"/> and may also be found on the recently opened Ex-Students' pathway. It was traditionally worn as part of the uniform on the [[tam-o-shanter]], until it was phased out in 1995. The badge is currently not worn on the academic uniform, partially due to its adoption by Pymble Ladies' College as their school crest in 1977.<ref name="GH299"/> It was, however, reintroduced in 2003 as an addition to the Beret of the PLC Pipes and Drums uniform, and is also used by the college's [[Alumni association|Ex-students' Union]], as it has been since 1905, with the addition of the words "Ex-students' Union" below.<ref name="GH299"/>

== Uniform ==
{|style="padding: 0.3em; float:right; margin-left:15px; border: 1px solid #B8C7D9; background:#f5faff; text-align:center; font-size: 85%; line-height: 1.0em"
|-
| style="background: #cedff2; padding: 0.3em; text-align:center;" |'''School Hymn'''
|-
|style="padding: 0.3em; text-align:center;"| '''The Golden Hope'''<br>''Written 1893 by Dr. [[William Walsham How]]<br>To the tune of "St. Fulbert"''{{Ref_label|c|c|none}}
|-
|style="padding: 0.3em; "|
O Jesus, strong and pure and true,<br>
Before Thy feet we bow;<br>
The grace of earlier years renew,<br>
And lead us onward now.<br>
<br>
The joyous life that year by year<br>
Within these walls is stored,<br>
The golden hope, the gladsome cheer,<br>
We bring to Thee, O Lord.<br>
<br>
Our faith endow with keener powers,<br>
With warmer glow our love;<br>
And draw these halting hearts of ours<br>
From earth to things above.<br>
<br>
In paths our bravest ones have trod,<br>
O make us strong to go,<br>
That we may give our lives to God,<br>
In serving man below.<br>
<br>
Scorn we the selfish aim or choice,<br>
And love's high precept keep,<br>
"Rejoice with those that do rejoice,<br>
And weep with those that weep".<br>
<br>
So hence shall flow fresh strength and grace,<br>
As from a full-fed spring,<br>
To make the world a better place,<br>
And life a worthier thing.<br><ref name="GH302">{{cite book| last = McFarlane| first = John| title = The Golden Hope: Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney 1888-1988| year = 1988| pages = p. 302| chapter =The School Hymn}}</ref>
|-
|}
When the College first opened in 1888 there was no uniform, instead the girls wore long cotton dresses, gloves and hat. A straw [[Boater (hat)|boater]] was introduced in the early 20th century, worn with a red and white hat band featuring the college crest with its [[burning bush]] woven into it in red. During this time [[Prefect]]s wore red silk arm-bands embroidered with a gold crest.<ref name="GH309">{{cite book| last = McFarlane| first = John| title = The Golden Hope: Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney 1888-1988| year = 1988| pages = pp. 309&ndash;311| chapter =The School Uniform}}</ref> 

The distinctive Black Watch Tartan of the college was introduced in 1918. Senior girls wore heavy box-pleated skirts and white blouses; junior girls wore pinafore dresses. All girls wore a navy blazer and heavy woollen stockings. Prefects also wore a special hat badge with a ring of bright blue enamel. A black felt Breton was introduced for winter use, and no change was made until the introduction of the green beret in 1952.<ref name="GH309"/>
 
The current uniform for Year 11 and 12 was introduced in 1966. It was designed by the senior students of 1965 and consists of a Black Watch kilt, white blouse, green blazer, green jumper or vest, black stockings for winter and bottle green knee-high socks for summer, and black leather lace-up shoes. Girls of [[Scotland|Scottish]] origin are permitted wear the [[kilt pin]] representing their family or [[Scottish clan|clan]] name, rather than the standard school pin. A green and Black Watch [[tam-o-shanter]] (known as 'the Beret') was also introduced for all grades a few years earlier.<ref name="GH309"/> 

The girls found the school's distinctive Beret difficult to wear, so it was phased out in 1995.<ref name="Aurora1995">{{Citation | title=Happenings | newspaper=Aurora Australis: The Magazine of the Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney | year=1995}}</ref> It was replaced by the current [[Panama hat]], but the Beret was reintroduced in 2003 as an addition to the [[Pipes and Drums]] uniform. 

The current junior (R&ndash;10) uniform was introduced in 1997. In summer, girls are required to wear a Black Watch tunic, short-sleeve white blouse, green blazer with tartan piping, short green socks and black leather shoes. The winter uniform consists of the tunic, long-sleeve white blouse, the blazer, green jumper or vest, Black Watch Tartan tie, Black Watch Tartan scarf and either green knee-high socks or black stockings.<ref name=BoardingHandbook>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public/boardinghousehandbook.pdf |title=Boarding House Handbook |accessdate=2007-06-21 |year=2006 |format=PDF |work=Boarding|publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College}}</ref> School pockets are awarded for student achievements, and are [[Embroidery|embroidered]] in red on the pockets of junior blazers (R&ndash;10 girls), and white on the left-breast of senior blazers (11&ndash;12 girls).

[[Image:Plcuniform1950.jpg|thumb|180px|PLC students in uniform, 1950]]
=== College tartan ===   
The school has adopted the [[Black Watch]] [[Tartan]] of the [[Black Watch|Royal Highland Regiment]] as its school and [[Pipe band|Pipes and Drums]] uniform. PLC was granted permission to wear the tartan after its brother school, [[The Scots College]], was issued a [[Decree|royal decree]] allowing them to use Black Watch as their Pipes & Drums and [[Cadets]] uniform. The Black Watch is the oldest of the highland regiments. The 1958 ''Aurora Australis'' (the school [[yearbook]]) explained the tartan's origin: "This tartan was specially designed for the regiment to prevent the jealousy which would have been aroused, if any existing clan tartan had been used."<ref name="Aurora1958">{{Citation | title=Tartan of the Black Watch | newspaper=Aurora Australis: The Magazine of the Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney | year=1958}}</ref>

== House system ==
The [[house system]] was established by Dr. John Marden, shortly after the opening of the school, with three houses: East, West and Boarders. In 1924 the senior houses were reorganised and renamed Kinross, Harper and Ferguson (with Anderson added in 1968), followed in 1926 by the introduction of junior houses, named Vicars and [[Ewen Neil McQueen|McQueen]] (with Thompson added in 1937).<ref name="GH65">{{cite book| last = McFarlane| first = John| title = The Golden Hope: Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney 1888-1988| year = 1988| pages = pp. 65 & 138}}</ref>  
The school moved to four houses in 1979, from primary to secondary, and thus the junior houses disappeared.<ref name="GH65"/> 
Finally, two new houses named Pickard and Wilkie were introduced in 1995. The Houses are named after women and men who have made a significant contribution to the life of the College.<ref name=PLCHouses/>

;Anderson
Mrs E.O. Anderson (1885&ndash;1985) attended PLC from 1898 to 1902. She was an original member of the Committee of the Ex-Students' Union in 1906, then President (1927&ndash;1932), and Patroness from 1936. In 1932 she petitioned the Assembly for the appointment of women to the PLC Council. Anderson was a member of the Council (1932&ndash;1958), and a benefactor to the College all her life.<ref name=PLCHouses>{{cite web |url=http://www.plc.nsw.edu.au/public2/house_system.asp |title=House System |accessdate=2007-04-23 |work=History |publisher=Presbyterian Ladies' College}}</ref> 

;Ferguson
[[John Ferguson (clergyman)|Rev John Ferguson]] (1852&ndash;1925) was a [[minister (Christianity)|minister]] of St Stephen's Church, Sydney, and in 1917, Acting Principal of [[St Andrew's College, Sydney|St Andrew's Theological College]] at the [[University of Sydney]]. He was appointed Senior [[Chaplain]] and Chairman of the PLC Council in 1913, serving until 1923.<ref name=PLCHouses/> 

;Harper
[[Andrew Harper|Rev Dr Andrew Harper]] (1844&ndash;1936) was the third Principal of [[Presbyterian Ladies' College, Melbourne|PLC Melbourne]] (1879&ndash;1888). He then lectured at [[Ormond College (University of Melbourne)|Ormond Theological College]], [[Melbourne, Victoria|Melbourne]] before coming to Sydney, where he was Principal of St Andrew's Theological College (1902&ndash;1923). He was Chairman of the PLC Council from 1907 until 1913.<ref name=PLCHouses/>  

;Kinross
Rev Dr John Kinross (1833&ndash;1908) was a Presbyterian minister at [[Kiama, New South Wales|Kiama]] (1858&ndash;1875). He then became Principal of St Andrew's Theological College from 1875 until 1901, and Chairman of the PLC Council from 1888 until 1906.<ref name=Kinross>{{cite web |url=http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A050040b.htmoffset=0&place_seq=2396 |title=Kinross, John (1833 - 1908) |accessdate=2007-04-23 |last=Dougan |first=Alan |year=1974 |work=Australian Dictionary of Biography |publisher= Melbourne University Press |pages=pp. 33&ndash;34}}</ref><ref name=PLCHouses/> 

;Pickard
Marion Pickard was appointed to the College as a teaching governess in June 1888. She was Lady [[Superintendent (education)|Superintendent]] from 1894 until her resignation in 1907. In 1905 Pickard was elected the first President of the Ex-Students' Union.<ref name=PLCHouses/>  

;Wilkie
Dr Helen Wilkie (1895&ndash;1984) was the second Headmistress at [[Presbyterian Ladies' College, Armidale|PLC Armidale]] (1938&ndash;1941), and then the fourth Principal of PLC Sydney (1942&ndash;1946). On her appointment to Croydon she was immediately confronted with the takeover by the [[Royal Australian Air Force|RAAF]], and organised the move of the College to Strathfield.<ref name=PLCHouses/>

==Ex-Students' Union==
'''The Ex-Students' Union''' is the school's [[alumni association]], [[Inauguration|inaugurated]] on the evening of [[9 December]] [[1905]]. At the invitation of Dr. Marden several former students discussed the proposal, elected Marion Pickard (who was at that time Lady [[Superintendent (education)|Superintendent]]) as their President, and formed a committee to produce a [[Constitution (corporate)|constitution]]. These actions were confirmed at a General Meeting on Jersey Day 1906, and the committee took office until 1907. 
In the beginning, the main objectives of the Union were "the accumulation of a special fund to be devoted to the erection of a [[chapel]] and library at the College, and an Ex-Students' prize to be awarded annually to the girl most proficient in work and sport."{{Ref_label|d|d|none}}<ref name="GH312">{{cite book| last = McFarlane| first = John| title = The Golden Hope: Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney 1888-1988| year = 1988| pages = pp. 312&ndash;317| chapter =The Ex-Students' Union}}</ref>

The Union achieved much in its first few years: renting a building in the [[Sydney central business district|CBD]] to serve as a club and committee meeting place, making garments for [[hospital]]s, visiting [[Kindergarten]]s, the [[YWCA]], Home of Peace, Infants' Home and the [[Royal Institute for Deaf and Blind Children]]. An Ex-Students' [[Orchestra]] and Dramatic Club were formed, and [[Tennis]] and [[Croquet]] matches were held between current and former pupils.<ref name="GH312"/>

In 1916 the Pymble College was opened and its first Ex-Students' Union expressed an interest in joining that of PLC. Subsequently a combined Union was formed, known as the PLC Croydon and Pymble Ex-Students' Union, and an Ex-Students' prize was established at Pymble on the same conditions as at Croydon.<ref name="GH312"/>

One of the Union's most significant contributions to the school was planned following the death of Dr. Marden in 1924. With the desire to provide Marden with a "fitting and lasting memorial",<ref name="GH312"/> it was decided that a library, to be called the John Marden Memorial Library, should be built at the Croydon College. This building was opened by Mrs. Marden in 1927 and although no longer suitable as a library due its size, it remains a treasured part of the school.<ref name="GH312"/>

In 1929, it was proposed that "Pymble students should form a separate Union"<ref name="GH312"/> and that an equitable division of Union funds should be undertaken. This explains the two separate groups that exist today, however, it is still not uncommon for Pymble students to attend Croydon [[reunion]]s and events, particularly regional or interstate activities.<ref name="GH312"/>

=== Notable alumnae ===
{{Main|List of Old Girls of PLC Sydney}}[[Image:Florencetaylor.jpg|thumb|right|110px|Florence Taylor, Class of 1896]]
[[Alumnae]] of the Presbyterian Ladies' College, Sydney are commonly referred to as PLC Old Girls, and may elect to join the schools alumni association, the PLC Ex-Students' Union.<ref name="GH312"/> 

In 2001, ''[[The Sun-Herald]]'' ranked PLC Sydney fourth in Australia's top ten girls' schools, based on the number of its alumni mentioned in the ''[[Who's Who in Australia]]'' (a listing of notable Australians).<ref name=WhosWho/>{{Ref_label|a|a|none}} Among these women are [[Sibyl Morrison]], the first female barrister in New South Wales,<ref name=SMorrison>{{cite encyclopedia| last = O'Brien| first = Joan M| encyclopedia =Australian Dictionary of Biography| title = Morrison, Sibyl Enid Vera Munro (1895 - 1961)| url = http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A100580b.htm| accessdate =  2007-08-01| edition = Online| year = 1986| publisher = Melbourne University Press| volume =10| location = Melbourne| pages =  p.596}}</ref> [[Marie Byles]], the first practicing female solicitor in New South Wales,<ref name=MByles>{{cite web|url = http://www.nsw.nationaltrust.org.au/properties/files/mariebyles_online.pdf|title = Marie Byles: A Spirited Life|accessdate = 2007-08-01|date = 2006|format = PDF|work = National Trust Online Exhibition |publisher = The National Trust of Australia (NSW)}}</ref> [[Jessie Aspinall]], the first female junior resident medical officer at [[Royal Prince Alfred Hospital]],<ref name=JAspinall>{{cite encyclopedia| last = Durie| first = E. Beatrix| encyclopedia =Australian Dictionary of Biography| title = Aspinall, Jessie Strahorn (1880 - 1953)| url = http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A070122b.htm| accessdate = 2007-08-01| edition = Online| year = 1979| publisher = Melbourne University Press| volume = 7| location = Melbourne| pages = p.118}}</ref> and [[Florence Mary Taylor]], the first qualified female architect and first woman to train as an engineer in Australia, and the first woman in Australia to fly in a heavier-than-air craft.<ref name=FMTaylor>{{cite web|url = http://www.womenaustralia.info/biogs/IMP0064b.htm
|title = Taylor, Florence Mary (1879 - 1969)|accessdate = 2007-08-01|last = Heywood|first = Anne|date = 2002-07-04|format = HTML|work =Australian Women Biographical Entry |publisher=National Foundation for Australian Women}}</ref>

